Japanese Stock Futures, Australian Shares Advance on Mubarak's Resignation

-- B y   A k i k o   I k e d a   a n d   K o t a r o   T s u n e t o m i
-- 
2011-02-13T23:54:27Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-13/japanese-stock-futures-australian-shares-advance-on-mubarak-s-resignation.html
Japanese stock futures rose after
Egyptian President  Hosni Mubarak ’s resignation and as the yen
weakened. Australian stocks climbed.  American depositary receipts of Nissan Motor Co., which
receives more than 75 percent of its revenue abroad, jumped 4.5
percent from the last closing share price in Tokyo. Those of
Kyocera Corp., an electronics maker that gets more than half of
its sales abroad, climbed 2.9 percent. BHP Billiton Ltd., the
world’s No. 1 mining company, rallied 1.3 percent in Sydney
today after metal prices increased.  After Mubarak resigned, “the worst is behind us, although
there’s still concern whether power will be transferred smoothly
in Egypt,” said  Kazuhiro Takahashi , a general manager at Tokyo-
based Daiwa Securities Capital Markets Co. “The yen’s slide
against the dollar will likely support the market.”  Futures on Japan’s  Nikkei 225  Stock Average expiring in
March closed at 10,705 in  Chicago  on Feb. 11, compared with
10,620 in Osaka. They were bid in the pre-market at 10,690 in  Osaka , Japan, at 8:05 a.m. local time. Japan’s market was closed
Feb. 11 for a holiday. Australia’s S&P/ASX 200 Index rose 0.5
percent today. New Zealand’s NZX 50 Index climbed 0.1 percent in
Wellington.  Futures on the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index were little
changed today. In  New York , the index advanced 0.6 percent to
1,329.15 on Feb. 11 as Mubarak’s resignation and a jump in
consumer confidence to an eight-month high bolstered optimism in
the global economic recovery.  U.S. Consumer Confidence  The preliminary estimate for Thomson Reuters/University of
Michigan index of U.S. consumer sentiment for February climbed
to 75.1.  The MSCI Asia Pacific Index fell 1.4 percent as of the
close on Feb. 11, compared with gains of 5.7 percent by the S&P
500 and 4.4 percent by the Stoxx Europe 600 Index. Stocks in the
Asian benchmark are valued at 13.9 times estimated earnings on
average, compared with 13.9 times for the  S&P 500  and 11.4 times
for the Stoxx 600.  The yen depreciated to as low as 83.57 against the dollar,
compared with 82.57 at the close of  stock trading  in Tokyo on
Feb. 10. A weaker yen boosts the value of overseas income at
Japanese companies when converted into their home currency.  The London Metal Exchange Index of prices for six
industrial metals including copper and aluminum rose 0.1 percent
on Feb. 11.  Japan’s economy contracted 1.1 percent on an annual basis
in the quarter ended December, according to the Cabinet Office.  To contact the reporters on this story:
